# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crystallography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] where the *ni* are any integers, and **a***i* are *primitive translation vectors*, or *primitive vectors*, which lie in different directions (not necessarily mutually perpendicular) and span the lattice.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The choice of primitive vectors for a given Bravais lattice is not unique.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] A fundamental aspect of any Bravais lattice is that, for any choice of direction, the lattice appears exactly the same from each of the discrete lattice points when looking in that chosen direction.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The Bravais lattice concept is used to formally define a *crystalline arrangement* and its (finite) frontiers.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] A crystal is made up of one or more atoms, called the *basis* or *motif*, at each lattice point.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The *basis* may consist of atoms, molecules, or polymer strings of solid matter, and the lattice provides the locations of the basis.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Two Bravais lattices are often considered equivalent if they have isomorphic symmetry groups.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In this sense, there are 5 possible Bravais lattices in 2-dimensional space and 14 possible Bravais lattices in 3-dimensional space.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The 14 possible symmetry groups of Bravais lattices are 14 of the 230 space groups.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In the context of the space group classification, the Bravais lattices are also called Bravais classes, Bravais arithmetic classes, or Bravais flocks.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In crystallography, there is the concept of a unit cell which comprises the space between adjacent lattice points as well as any atoms in that space.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] A unit cell is defined as a space that, when translated through a subset of all vectors described by $\mathbf {R} =n_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+n_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+n_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ , fills the lattice space without overlapping or voids.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] There are mainly two types of unit cells: primitive unit cells and conventional unit cells.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] A primitive cell is the very smallest component of a lattice (or crystal) which, when stacked together with lattice translation operations, reproduces the whole lattice (or crystal).
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Note that the translations must be lattice translation operations that cause the lattice to appear unchanged after the translation.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] If arbitrary translations were allowed, one could make a primitive cell half the size of the true one, and translate twice as often, as an example.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In either definition, the primitive cell is characterized by its small size.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] There are clearly many choices of cell that can reproduce the whole lattice when stacked (two lattice halves, for instance), and the minimum size requirement distinguishes the primitive cell from all these other valid repeating units.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] If the lattice or crystal is 2-dimensional, the primitive cell has a minimum area; likewise in 3 dimensions the primitive cell has a minimum volume.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Despite this rigid minimum-size requirement, there is not one unique choice of primitive unit cell.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In fact, all cells whose borders are primitive translation vectors will be primitive unit cells.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The fact that there is not a unique choice of primitive translation vectors for a given lattice leads to the multiplicity of possible primitive unit cells.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Conventional unit cells, on the other hand, are not necessarily minimum-size cells.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] They are chosen purely for convenience and are often used for illustration purposes.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Primitive unit cells are defined as unit cells with the smallest volume for a given crystal.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] (A crystal is a lattice and a basis at every lattice point.) To have the smallest cell volume, a primitive unit cell must contain (1) only one lattice point and (2) the minimum amount of basis constituents (e.g., the minimum number of atoms in a basis).
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] For the former requirement, counting the number of lattice points in a unit cell is such that, if a lattice point is shared by *m* adjacent unit cells around that lattice point, then the point is counted as 1/*m*.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The latter requirement is necessary since there are crystals that can be described by more than one combination of a lattice and a basis.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] For example, a crystal, viewed as a lattice with a single kind of atom located at every lattice point (the simplest basis form), may also be viewed as a lattice with a basis of two atoms.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In this case, a primitive unit cell is a unit cell having only one lattice point in the first way of describing the crystal in order to ensure the smallest unit cell volume.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Among all possible primitive cells for a given crystal, an obvious primitive cell may be the parallelepiped formed by a chosen set of primitive translation vectors.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] (Again, these vectors must make a lattice with the minimum amount of basis constituents.) That is, the set of all points $\mathbf {r} =x_{1}\mathbf {a} _{1}+x_{2}\mathbf {a} _{2}+x_{3}\mathbf {a} _{3}$ where $0\leq x_{i}<1$ and $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ is the chosen primitive vector.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] This primitive cell does not always show the clear symmetry of a given crystal.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In this case, a conventional unit cell easily displaying the crystal symmetry is often used.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The conventional unit cell volume will be an integer-multiple of the primitive unit cell volume.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In two dimensions, any lattice can be specified by the length of its two primitive translation vectors and the angle between them.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] There are an infinite number of possible lattices one can describe in this way.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Some way to categorize different types of lattices is desired.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] One way to do so is to recognize that some lattices have inherent symmetry.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] One can impose conditions on the length of the primitive translation vectors and on the angle between them to produce various symmetric lattices.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] These symmetries themselves are categorized into different types, such as point groups (which includes mirror symmetries, inversion symmetries and rotation symmetries) and translational symmetries.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Thus, lattices can be categorized based on what point group or translational symmetry applies to them.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In two dimensions, the most basic point group corresponds to rotational invariance under 2π and π, or 1- and 2-fold rotational symmetry.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] This actually applies automatically to all 2D lattices, and is the most general point group.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Lattices contained in this group (technically all lattices, but conventionally all lattices that don't fall into any of the other point groups) are called oblique lattices.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Thus altogether there are 5 Bravais lattices in 2 dimensions.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Likewise, in 3 dimensions, there are 14 Bravais lattices: 1 general "wastebasket" category (triclinic) and 13 more categories.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] These 14 lattice types are classified by their point groups into 7 lattice systems (triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, cubic, rhombohedral, and hexagonal).
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In two-dimensional space there are 5 Bravais lattices, grouped into four lattice systems, shown in the table below.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Below each diagram is the Pearson symbol for that Bravais lattice.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The unit cells are specified according to the relative lengths of the cell edges (*a* and *b*) and the angle between them (*θ*).
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The area of the unit cell can be calculated by evaluating the norm ‖**a** × **b**‖, where **a** and **b** are the lattice vectors.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In three-dimensional space there are 14 Bravais lattices.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] These are obtained by combining one of the seven lattice systems with one of the centering types.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Not all combinations of lattice systems and centering types are needed to describe all of the possible lattices, as it can be shown that several of these are in fact equivalent to each other.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] For example, the monoclinic I lattice can be described by a monoclinic C lattice by different choice of crystal axes.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Similarly, all A- or B-centred lattices can be described either by a C- or P-centering.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] This reduces the number of combinations to 14 conventional Bravais lattices, shown in the table below.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The unit cells are specified according to six lattice parameters which are the relative lengths of the cell edges (*a*, *b*, *c*) and the angles between them (*α*, *β*, *γ*), where *α* is the angle between *b* and *c*, *β* is the angle between *a* and *c*, and *γ* is the angle between *a* and *b*.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The volume of the unit cell can be calculated by evaluating the triple product **a** · (**b** × **c**), where **a**, **b**, and **c** are the lattice vectors.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Some basic information for the lattice systems and Bravais lattices in three dimensions is summarized in the diagram at the beginning of this page.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The seven sided polygon (heptagon) and the number 7 at the centre indicate the seven lattice systems.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] The inner heptagons indicate the lattice angles, lattice parameters, Bravais lattices and Schöenflies notations for the respective lattice systems.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] In four dimensions, there are 64 Bravais lattices.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Of these, 23 are primitive and 41 are centered.
[src:crystallography/bravais-lattice] Ten Bravais lattices split into enantiomorphic pairs.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] In crystallography, a **crystal system** is a set of point groups (a group of geometric symmetries with at least one fixed point).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A **lattice system** is a set of Bravais lattices (an infinite array of discrete points).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Space groups (symmetry groups of a configuration in space) are classified into crystal systems according to their point groups, and into lattice systems according to their Bravais lattices.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Crystal systems that have space groups assigned to a common lattice system are combined into a **crystal family**.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The seven crystal systems are *triclinic*, *monoclinic*, *orthorhombic*, *tetragonal*, *trigonal*, *hexagonal*, and *cubic*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Informally, two crystals are in the same crystal system if they have similar symmetries (though there are many exceptions).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Crystals can be classified in three ways: lattice systems, crystal systems and crystal families.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The various classifications are often confused: in particular the trigonal crystal system is often confused with the rhombohedral lattice system, and the term "crystal system" is sometimes used to mean "lattice system" or "crystal family".
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A lattice system is a group of lattices with the same set of lattice point groups.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The 14 Bravais lattices are grouped into seven lattice systems: triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, rhombohedral, hexagonal, and cubic.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A crystal system is a set of point groups in which the point groups themselves and their corresponding space groups are assigned to a lattice system.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Of the 32 crystallographic point groups that exist in three dimensions, most are assigned to only one lattice system, in which case both the crystal and lattice systems have the same name.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] However, five point groups are assigned to two lattice systems, rhombohedral and hexagonal, because both exhibit threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] These point groups are assigned to the trigonal crystal system.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A crystal family is determined by lattices and point groups.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] It is formed by combining crystal systems that have space groups assigned to a common lattice system.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] In three dimensions, the hexagonal and trigonal crystal systems are combined into one hexagonal crystal family.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Five of the crystal systems are essentially the same as five of the lattice systems.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The hexagonal and trigonal crystal systems differ from the hexagonal and rhombohedral lattice systems.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] These are combined into the hexagonal crystal family.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Note: there is no "trigonal" lattice system.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] To avoid confusion of terminology, the term "trigonal lattice" is not used.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The point symmetry of a structure can be further described as follows.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Consider the points that make up the structure, and reflect them all through a single point, so that (*x*,*y*,*z*) becomes (−*x*,−*y*,−*z*).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] If the original structure and inverted structure are identical, then the structure is *centrosymmetric*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Still, even in the non-centrosymmetric case, the inverted structure can in some cases be rotated to align with the original structure.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] This is a non-centrosymmetric *achiral* structure.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] If the inverted structure cannot be rotated to align with the original structure, then the structure is *chiral* or *enantiomorphic* and its symmetry group is *enantiomorphic*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A direction (meaning a line without an arrow) is called *polar* if its two-directional senses are geometrically or physically different.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A symmetry direction of a crystal that is polar is called a *polar axis*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Groups containing a polar axis are called *polar*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A polar crystal possesses a unique polar axis (more precisely, all polar axes are parallel).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Some geometrical or physical property is different at the two ends of this axis: for example, there might develop a dielectric polarization as in pyroelectric crystals.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] A polar axis can occur only in non-centrosymmetric structures.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] There cannot be a mirror plane or twofold axis perpendicular to the polar axis, because they would make the two directions of the axis equivalent.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The crystal structures of chiral biological molecules (such as protein structures) can only occur in the 65 enantiomorphic space groups (biological molecules are usually chiral).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] There are seven different kinds of lattice systems, and each kind of lattice system has four different kinds of centerings (primitive, base-centered, body-centered, face-centered).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] However, not all of the combinations are unique; some of the combinations are equivalent while other combinations are not possible due to symmetry reasons.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] This reduces the number of unique lattices to the 14 Bravais lattices.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The distribution of the 14 Bravais lattices into 7 lattice systems is given in the following table.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] In geometry and crystallography, a **Bravais lattice** is a category of translative symmetry groups (also known as lattices) in three directions.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] where *n*1, *n*2, and *n*3 are integers and **a**1, **a**2, and **a**3 are three non-coplanar vectors, called *primitive vectors*.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] These lattices are classified by the space group of the lattice itself, viewed as a collection of points; there are 14 Bravais lattices in three dimensions; each belongs to one lattice system only.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] They represent the maximum symmetry a structure with the given translational symmetry can have.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] All crystalline materials (not including quasicrystals) must, by definition, fit into one of these arrangements.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] For convenience a Bravais lattice is depicted by a unit cell which is a factor 1, 2, 3, or 4 larger than the primitive cell.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Depending on the symmetry of a crystal or other pattern, the fundamental domain is again smaller, up to a factor 48.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The Bravais lattices were studied by Moritz Ludwig Frankenheim in 1842, who found that there were 15 Bravais lattices.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] In two-dimensional space, there are four crystal systems (oblique, rectangular, square, hexagonal), four crystal families (oblique, rectanguar, square, hexagonal), and four lattice systems (oblique, rectangular, square, and hexagonal).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] ‌The four-dimensional unit cell is defined by four edge lengths (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) and six interaxial angles (*α*, *β*, *γ*, *δ*, *ε*, *ζ*).
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The names here are given according to Whittaker.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] They are almost the same as in Brown *et al.*, with exception for names of the crystal families 9, 13, and 22.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The names for these three families according to Brown *et al.* are given in parentheses.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The relation between four-dimensional crystal families, crystal systems, and lattice systems is shown in the following table.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Enantiomorphic systems are marked with an asterisk.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The number of enantiomorphic pairs is given in parentheses.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Here the term "enantiomorphic" has a different meaning than in the table for three-dimensional crystal classes.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] The latter means, that enantiomorphic point groups describe chiral (enantiomorphic) structures.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] In the current table, "enantiomorphic" means that a group itself (considered as a geometric object) is enantiomorphic, like enantiomorphic pairs of three-dimensional space groups P31 and P32, P4122 and P4322.
[src:crystallography/crystal-system] Starting from four-dimensional space, point groups also can be enantiomorphic in this sense.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography is a broad topic, and many of its subareas, such as X-ray crystallography, are themselves important scientific topics.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography ranges from the fundamentals of crystal structure to the mathematics of crystal geometry, including those that are not periodic or quasicrystals.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] At the atomic scale it can involve the use of X-ray diffraction to produce experimental data that the tools of X-ray crystallography can convert into detailed positions of atoms, and sometimes electron density.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] At larger scales it includes experimental tools such as orientational imaging to examine the relative orientations at the grain boundary in materials.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography plays a key role in many areas of biology, chemistry, and physics, as well as in emerging developments in these fields.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Before the 20th century, the study of crystals was based on physical measurements of their geometry using a goniometer.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] This involved measuring the angles of crystal faces relative to each other and to theoretical reference axes (crystallographic axes), and establishing the symmetry of the crystal in question.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The position in 3D space of each crystal face is plotted on a stereographic net such as a Wulff net or Lambert net.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The pole to each face is plotted on the net.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Each point is labelled with its Miller index.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The final plot allows the symmetry of the crystal to be established.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The discovery of X-rays and electrons in the last decade of the 19th century enabled the determination of crystal structures on the atomic scale, which brought about the modern era of crystallography.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The first X-ray diffraction experiment was conducted in 1912 by Max von Laue, while electron diffraction was first realized in 1927 in the Davisson–Germer experiment and parallel work by George Paget Thomson and Alexander Reid.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] These developed into the two main branches of crystallography, X-ray crystallography and electron diffraction.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The quality and throughput of solving crystal structures greatly improved in the second half of the 20th century, with the developments of customized instruments and phasing algorithms.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Nowadays, crystallography is an interdisciplinary field, supporting theoretical and experimental discoveries in various domains.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Modern-day scientific instruments for crystallography vary from laboratory-sized equipment, such as diffractometers and electron microscopes, to dedicated large facilities, such as photoinjectors, synchrotron light sources and free-electron lasers.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallographic methods depend mainly on analysis of the diffraction patterns of a sample targeted by a beam of some type.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] X-rays are most commonly used; other beams used include electrons or neutrons.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallographers often explicitly state the type of beam used, as in the terms *X-ray diffraction, neutron diffraction* and *electron diffraction*.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] These three types of radiation interact with the specimen in different ways.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] It is hard to focus x-rays or neutrons, but since electrons are charged they can be focused and are used in electron microscopes to produce magnified images.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] There are many ways that transmission electron microscopy and related techniques such as scanning transmission electron microscopy, high-resolution electron microscopy can be used to obtain images with in many cases atomic resolution from which crystallographic information can be obtained.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] There are also other methods such as low-energy electron diffraction, low-energy electron microscopy and reflection high-energy electron diffraction which can be used to obtain crystallographic information about surfaces.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography is used by materials scientists to characterize different materials.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] In single crystals, the effects of the crystalline arrangement of atoms is often easy to see macroscopically because the natural shapes of crystals reflect the atomic structure.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] In addition, physical properties are often controlled by crystalline defects.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The understanding of crystal structures is an important prerequisite for understanding crystallographic defects.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Most materials do not occur as a single crystal, but are poly-crystalline in nature (they exist as an aggregate of small crystals with different orientations).
[src:crystallography/crystallography] As such, powder diffraction techniques, which take diffraction patterns of samples with a large number of crystals, play an important role in structural determination.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Other physical properties are also linked to crystallography.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] For example, the minerals in clay form small, flat, platelike structures.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Clay can be easily deformed because the platelike particles can slip along each other in the plane of the plates, yet remain strongly connected in the direction perpendicular to the plates.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Such mechanisms can be studied by crystallographic texture measurements.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallographic studies help elucidate the relationship between a material's structure and its properties, aiding in developing new materials with tailored characteristics.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] This understanding is crucial in various fields, including metallurgy, geology, and materials science.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Advancements in crystallographic techniques, such as electron diffraction and X-ray crystallography, continue to expand our understanding of material behavior at the atomic level.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] In another example, iron transforms from a body-centered cubic (bcc) structure called ferrite to a face-centered cubic (fcc) structure called austenite when it is heated.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The fcc structure is a close-packed structure unlike the bcc structure; thus the volume of the iron decreases when this transformation occurs.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography is useful in phase identification.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] When manufacturing or using a material, it is generally desirable to know what compounds and what phases are present in the material, as their composition, structure and proportions will influence the material's properties.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Each phase has a characteristic arrangement of atoms.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] X-ray or neutron diffraction can be used to identify which structures are present in the material, and thus which compounds are present.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Crystallography covers the enumeration of the symmetry patterns which can be formed by atoms in a crystal and for this reason is related to group theory.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] X-ray crystallography is the primary method for determining the molecular conformations of biological macromolecules, particularly protein and nucleic acids such as DNA and RNA.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The first crystal structure of a macromolecule was solved in 1958, a three-dimensional model of the myoglobin molecule obtained by X-ray analysis.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Electron diffraction has been used to determine some protein structures, most notably membrane proteins and viral capsids.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] Macromolecular structures determined through X-ray crystallography (and other techniques) are housed in the Protein Data Bank (PDB)–a freely accessible repository for the structures of proteins and other biological macromolecules.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] There are many molecular graphics codes available for visualising these structures.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The *International Tables for Crystallography* is an eight-book series that outlines the standard notations for formatting, describing and testing crystals.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The series contains books that covers analysis methods and the mathematical procedures for determining organic structure through x-ray crystallography, electron diffraction, and neutron diffraction.
[src:crystallography/crystallography] The International tables are focused on procedures, techniques and descriptions and do not list the physical properties of individual crystals themselves.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] In particular, a family of lattice planes of a given (direct) Bravais lattice is determined by three integers h, k, and l, the *Miller indices*.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] By convention, negative integers are written with a bar, as in 3 for −3.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The integers are usually written in lowest terms, i.e. their greatest common divisor should be 1.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Miller indices are also used to designate reflections in X-ray crystallography.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] In this case the integers are not necessarily in lowest terms, and can be thought of as corresponding to planes spaced such that the reflections from adjacent planes would have a phase difference of exactly one wavelength (2π), regardless of whether there are atoms on all these planes or not.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Miller indices were introduced in 1839 by the British mineralogist William Hallowes Miller, although an almost identical system (*Weiss parameters*) had already been used by German mineralogist Christian Samuel Weiss since 1817.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The method was also historically known as the Millerian system, and the indices as Millerian, although this is now rare.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The Miller indices are defined with respect to any choice of unit cell and not only with respect to primitive basis vectors, as is sometimes stated.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] There are two equivalent ways to define the meaning of the Miller indices: via a point in the reciprocal lattice, or as the inverse intercepts along the lattice vectors.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] In either case, one needs to choose the three lattice vectors **a**1, **a**2, and **a**3 that define the unit cell (note that the conventional unit cell may be larger than the primitive cell of the Bravais lattice, as the examples below illustrate).
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Given these, the three primitive reciprocal lattice vectors are also determined (denoted **b**1, **b**2, and **b**3).
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Because the coordinates are integers, this normal is itself always a reciprocal lattice vector.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The requirement of lowest terms means that it is the *shortest* reciprocal lattice vector in the given direction.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Equivalently, (*hkl*) denotes a plane that intercepts the three points **a**1/*h*, **a**2/*k*, and **a**3/*l*, or some multiple thereof.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] That is, the Miller indices are proportional to the *inverses* of the intercepts of the plane, in the basis of the lattice vectors.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] If one of the indices is zero, it means that the planes do not intersect that axis (the intercept is "at infinity").
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The related notation [*hkl*] denotes the *direction*: $h\mathbf {a} _{1}+k\mathbf {a} _{2}+\ell \mathbf {a} _{3}.$ That is, it uses the direct lattice basis instead of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Note that [*hkl*] is *not* generally normal to the (*hkl*) planes, except in a cubic lattice as described below.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For the special case of simple cubic crystals, the lattice vectors are orthogonal and of equal length (usually denoted a), as are those of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Thus, in this common case, the Miller indices (*hkl*) and [*hkl*] both simply denote normals/directions in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For face-centered cubic and body-centered cubic lattices, the primitive lattice vectors are not orthogonal.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] However, in these cases the Miller indices are conventionally defined relative to the lattice vectors of the cubic supercell and hence are again simply the Cartesian directions.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For hexagonal and rhombohedral lattice systems, the **Bravais–Miller** system is typically used, which uses four indices (*h* *k* *i* *l*) that obey the constraint $h+k+i=0.$ Here h, k and l are identical to the corresponding Miller indices, and i is a redundant index.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] This four-index scheme for labeling planes in a hexagonal lattice makes permutation symmetries apparent.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For example, the similarity between (110) ≡ (1120) and (120) ≡ (1210) is more obvious when the redundant index is shown.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] In the figure at right, the (001) plane has a 3-fold symmetry: it remains unchanged by a rotation of 1/3 (2π/3 rad, 120°).
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The [100], [010] and the [110] directions are really similar.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] There are also *ad hoc* schemes (e.g. in the transmission electron microscopy literature) for indexing hexagonal *lattice vectors* (rather than reciprocal lattice vectors or planes) with four indices.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] However they do not operate by similarly adding a redundant index to the regular three-index set.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Thus as you can see, four-index zone indices in square or angle brackets sometimes mix a single direct-lattice index on the right with reciprocal-lattice indices (normally in round or curly brackets) on the left.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Crystallographic directions are lines linking nodes (atoms, ions or molecules) of a crystal.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Similarly, crystallographic planes are *planes* linking nodes.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For all these reasons, it is important to determine the planes and thus to have a notation system.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Ordinarily, Miller indices are always integers by definition, and this constraint is physically significant.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] To understand this, suppose that we allow a plane (*abc*) where the Miller "indices" a, b and c (defined as above) are not necessarily integers.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] If a, b and c have rational ratios, then the same family of planes can be written in terms of integer indices (*hkl*) by scaling a, b and c appropriately: divide by the largest of the three numbers, and then multiply by the least common denominator.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] Thus, integer Miller indices implicitly include indices with all rational ratios.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] The reason why planes where the components (in the reciprocal-lattice basis) have rational ratios are of special interest is that these are the lattice planes: they are the only planes whose intersections with the crystal are 2d-periodic.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] For a plane (*abc*) where a, b and c have irrational ratios, on the other hand, the intersection of the plane with the crystal is *not* periodic.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] It forms an aperiodic pattern known as a quasicrystal.
[src:crystallography/miller-index] This construction corresponds precisely to the standard "cut-and-project" method of defining a quasicrystal, using a plane with irrational-ratio Miller indices.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In mathematics, physics and chemistry, a **space group** is the symmetry group of a repeating pattern in space, usually in three dimensions.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The elements of a space group (its symmetry operations) are the rigid transformations of the pattern that leave it unchanged.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Usually the term is applied to groups that repeat in all three dimensions, but the line groups and the wallpaper groups also apply, or can apply, to three-dimensional arrangements.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The space groups that repeat in all three dimensions are classified into 219 distinct types, or 230 types if chiral copies are considered distinct.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Space groups are discrete cocompact groups of isometries of an oriented Euclidean space in any number of dimensions.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In dimensions other than 3, they are sometimes called **Bieberbach groups**.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In crystallography, space groups are also called the **crystallographic** or **Fedorov groups**, and represent a description of the symmetry of the crystal.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Large collected sources of this information are available.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Space groups in 2 dimensions are the 17 wallpaper groups which have been known for several centuries, though the proof that the list was complete was only given in 1891, after the much more difficult classification of space groups had largely been completed.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In 1879 the German mathematician Leonhard Sohncke listed the 65 space groups (called Sohncke groups) whose elements preserve the chirality.
[src:crystallography/space-group] More accurately, he listed 66 groups, but both the Russian mathematician and crystallographer Evgraf Fedorov and the German mathematician Arthur Moritz Schoenflies noticed that two of them were really the same.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The correct list of 230 space groups was found by 1892 during correspondence between Fedorov and Schönflies.
[src:crystallography/space-group] William Barlow later enumerated the groups with a different method, but omitted four groups (Fdd2, I42d, P421d, and P421c).
[src:crystallography/space-group] A detailed description of the history of the discovery of the space groups has been written.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The space groups in three dimensions are made from combinations of the 32 crystallographic point groups with the 14 Bravais lattices, each of the latter belonging to one of 7 lattice systems.
[src:crystallography/space-group] What this means is that the action of any element of a given space group can be expressed as the action of an element of the appropriate point group followed optionally by a translation.
[src:crystallography/space-group] A space group is thus some combination of the translational symmetry of a unit cell (including lattice centering), the point group symmetry operations of reflection, rotation and improper rotation (also called rotoinversion), and the screw axis and glide plane symmetry operations.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The combination of all these symmetry operations results in a total of 230 different space groups describing all possible crystal symmetries.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The number of replicates of the asymmetric unit in a unit cell is thus the number of lattice points in the cell times the order of the point group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] This ranges from 1 in the case of space group P1 to 192 for a space group like Fm3m, the NaCl structure.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The elements of the space group fixing a point of space are the identity element, reflections, rotations and improper rotations, including inversion points.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The translations form a normal abelian subgroup of rank 3, called the Bravais lattice (so named after French physicist Auguste Bravais).
[src:crystallography/space-group] There are 14 possible types of Bravais lattice.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The quotient of the space group by the Bravais lattice is a finite group which is one of the 32 possible point groups.
[src:crystallography/space-group] A glide plane is a reflection in a plane, followed by a translation parallel with that plane.
[src:crystallography/space-group] This is noted by a, b, or c, depending on which axis the glide is along.
[src:crystallography/space-group] There is also the n glide, which is a glide along the half of a diagonal of a face, and the d glide, which is a fourth of the way along either a face or space diagonal of the unit cell.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The latter is called the diamond glide plane as it features in the diamond structure.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In 17 space groups, due to the centering of the cell, the glides occur in two perpendicular directions simultaneously, *i.e.* the same glide plane can be called b or c, a or b, a or c.
[src:crystallography/space-group] For example, group Abm2 could be also called Acm2, group Ccca could be called Cccb.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In 1992, it was suggested to use symbol e for such planes.
[src:crystallography/space-group] A screw axis is a rotation about an axis, followed by a translation along the direction of the axis.
[src:crystallography/space-group] These are noted by a number, n, to describe the degree of rotation, where the number is how many operations must be applied to complete a full rotation (e.g., 3 would mean a rotation one third of the way around the axis each time).
[src:crystallography/space-group] The degree of translation is then added as a subscript showing how far along the axis the translation is, as a portion of the parallel lattice vector.
[src:crystallography/space-group] So, 21 is a twofold rotation followed by a translation of ⁠1/2⁠ of the lattice vector.
[src:crystallography/space-group] where M is its matrix, D is its vector, and where the element transforms point x into point y.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In general, *D* = *D* (lattice) + *D*(*M*), where *D*(*M*) is a unique function of M that is zero for M being the identity.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The matrices M form a point group that is a basis of the space group; the lattice must be symmetric under that point group, but the crystal structure itself may not be symmetric under that point group as applied to any particular point (that is, without a translation).
[src:crystallography/space-group] For example, the diamond cubic structure does not have any point where the cubic point group applies.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The lattice dimension can be less than the overall dimension, resulting in a "subperiodic" space group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The 65 "Sohncke" space groups, not containing any mirrors, inversion points, improper rotations or glide planes, yield chiral crystals, not identical to their mirror image; whereas space groups that do include at least one of those give achiral crystals.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Achiral molecules sometimes form chiral crystals, but chiral molecules always form chiral crystals, in one of the space groups that permit this.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Among the 65 Sohncke groups are 22 that come in 11 enantiomorphic pairs.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Only certain combinations of symmetry elements are possible in a space group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Translations are always present, and the space group P1 has only translations and the identity element.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The presence of mirrors implies glide planes as well, and the presence of rotation axes implies screw axes as well, but the converses are not true.
[src:crystallography/space-group] An inversion and a mirror implies two-fold screw axes, and so on.
[src:crystallography/space-group] There are at least ten methods of naming space groups.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Some of these methods can assign several different names to the same space group, so altogether there are many thousands of different names.
[src:crystallography/space-group] publishes tables of all space group types, and assigns each a unique number from 1 to 230.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The numbering is arbitrary, except that groups with the same crystal system or point group are given consecutive numbers.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The Hermann–Mauguin (or international) notation describes the lattice and some generators for the group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] , which is the one most commonly used in crystallography, and usually consists of a set of four symbols.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The next three describe the most prominent symmetry operation visible when projected along one of the high symmetry directions of the crystal.
[src:crystallography/space-group] , with the addition of glide planes and screw axis, described above.
[src:crystallography/space-group] 21, showing that it exhibits primitive centering of the motif (i.e., once per unit cell), with a threefold screw axis and a twofold rotation axis.
[src:crystallography/space-group] in this example) denotes the symmetry along the major axis (c-axis in trigonal cases), the second (2 in this case) along axes of secondary importance (a and b) and the third symbol the symmetry in another direction.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In this space group the twofold axes are not along the a and b-axes but in a direction rotated by 30°.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The international symbols and international short symbols for some of the space groups were changed slightly between 1935 and 2002, so several space groups have 4 different international symbols in use.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The viewing directions of the 7 crystal systems are shown as follows.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Space group notation with an explicit origin.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Rotation, translation and axis-direction symbols are clearly separated and inversion centers are explicitly defined.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The construction and format of the notation make it particularly suited to computer generation of symmetry information.
[src:crystallography/space-group] For example, group number 3 has three Hall symbols: P 2y (P 1 2 1), P 2 (P 1 1 2), P 2x (P 2 1 1).
[src:crystallography/space-group] The space groups with given point group are numbered by 1, 2, 3, ...
[src:crystallography/space-group] (in the same order as their international number) and this number is added as a superscript to the Schönflies symbol for the point group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Some structure designation share the same space groups.
[src:crystallography/space-group] However, crystallographers would not use Strukturbericht notation to describe the space group, rather it would be used to describe a specific crystal structure (e.g. space group + atomic arrangement (motif)).
[src:crystallography/space-group] , given by the quotient of Euclidean space by the space group, rather than generators of the space group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] , and is not used much outside mathematics.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Some of the space groups have several different fibrifolds associated to them, so have several different fibrifold symbols.
[src:crystallography/space-group] There are (at least) 10 different ways to classify space groups into classes.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The relations between some of these are described in the following table.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Each classification system is a refinement of the ones below it.
[src:crystallography/space-group] To understand an explanation given here it may be necessary to understand the next one down.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Another classification of the space groups is called a fibrifold notation, according to the fibrifold structures on the corresponding orbifold.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The 219 affine space groups are divided into reducible and irreducible groups.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The reducible groups fall into 17 classes corresponding to the 17 wallpaper groups, and the remaining 35 irreducible groups are the same as the cubic groups and are classified separately.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In n dimensions, an affine space group, or Bieberbach group, is a discrete subgroup of isometries of n-dimensional Euclidean space with a compact fundamental domain.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Biberbach proved that the subgroup of translations of any such group contains n linearly independent translations, and is a free abelian subgroup of finite index, and is also the unique maximal normal abelian subgroup.
[src:crystallography/space-group] He also showed that in any dimension n there are only a finite number of possibilities for the isomorphism class of the underlying group of a space group, and moreover the action of the group on Euclidean space is unique up to conjugation by affine transformations.
[src:crystallography/space-group] This answers part of Hilbert's eighteenth problem.
[src:crystallography/space-group] It was shown that conversely any group that is the extension of **Z***n* by a finite group acting faithfully is an affine space group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Combining these results shows that classifying space groups in n dimensions up to conjugation by affine transformations is essentially the same as classifying isomorphism classes for groups that are extensions of **Z***n* by a finite group acting faithfully.
[src:crystallography/space-group] It is essential in Bieberbach's theorems to assume that the group acts as isometries; the theorems do not generalize to discrete cocompact groups of affine transformations of Euclidean space.
[src:crystallography/space-group] A counter-example is given by the 3-dimensional Heisenberg group of the integers acting by translations on the Heisenberg group of the reals, identified with 3-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:crystallography/space-group] This is a discrete cocompact group of affine transformations of space, but does not contain a subgroup **Z**3.
[src:crystallography/space-group] This table gives the number of space group types in small dimensions, including the numbers of various classes of space group.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The numbers of enantiomorphic pairs are given in parentheses.
[src:crystallography/space-group] One is the group of integers and the other is the infinite dihedral group; see symmetry groups in one dimension.
[src:crystallography/space-group] These **2D space groups** are also called **wallpaper groups** or **plane groups**.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In 3D, there are 230 crystallographic space group types, which reduces to 219 affine space group types because of some types being different from their mirror image; these are said to differ by *enantiomorphous character* (e.g.
[src:crystallography/space-group] They were enumerated independently by multiple researchers.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The 4894 4-dimensional groups have been enumerated (and corrected) over time; originally 4895 were listed due to one too many enantiomorphic groups being present.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Enumeration of dimension 6 was completed first; later the corrected figures were found.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The initially published number of 826 Lattice types in was corrected to 841.
[src:crystallography/space-group] In addition to crystallographic space groups there are also magnetic space groups (also called two-color (black and white) crystallographic groups or Shubnikov groups).
[src:crystallography/space-group] These symmetries contain an element known as time reversal.
[src:crystallography/space-group] They treat time as an additional dimension, and the group elements can include time reversal as reflection in it.
[src:crystallography/space-group] They are of importance in magnetic structures that contain ordered unpaired spins, i.e. ferro-, ferri- or antiferromagnetic structures as studied by neutron diffraction.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The time reversal element flips a magnetic spin while leaving all other structure the same and it can be combined with a number of other symmetry elements.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Including time reversal there are 1651 magnetic space groups in 3D.
[src:crystallography/space-group] It has also been possible to construct magnetic versions for other overall and lattice dimensions.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Frieze groups are magnetic 1D line groups and layer groups are magnetic wallpaper groups, and the axial 3D point groups are magnetic 2D point groups.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Note: An e plane is a double glide plane, one having glides in two different directions.
[src:crystallography/space-group] They are found in seven orthorhombic, five tetragonal and five cubic space groups, all with centered lattice.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The use of the symbol e became official circa 2002.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The lattice system can be found as follows.
[src:crystallography/space-group] If the crystal system is not trigonal then the lattice system is of the same type.
[src:crystallography/space-group] If the crystal system is trigonal, then the lattice system is hexagonal unless the space group is one of the seven in the rhombohedral lattice system consisting of the 7 trigonal space groups in the table above whose name begins with R.
[src:crystallography/space-group] The Bravais lattice of the space group is determined by the lattice system together with the initial letter of its name, which for the non-rhombohedral groups is P, I, F, A or C, standing for the principal, body centered, face centered, A-face centered or C-face centered lattices.
[src:crystallography/space-group] There are seven rhombohedral space groups, with initial letter R.
[src:crystallography/space-group] Axes of rotation, rotoinversion axes and mirror planes remain unchanged.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] In geometry, biology, mineralogy and solid state physics, a **unit cell** is a repeating unit formed by the vectors spanning the points of a lattice.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Despite its suggestive name, the unit cell (unlike a unit vector, for example) does not necessarily have unit size, or even a particular size at all.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Rather, the primitive cell is the closest analogy to a unit vector, since it has a determined size for a given lattice and is the basic building block from which larger cells are constructed.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Geometrically, this is a special case of a fundamental domain of a group (the translation symmetries) acting on a topological space (Euclidean space).
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The concept is used particularly in describing crystal structure in two and three dimensions, though it makes sense in all dimensions.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] A lattice can be characterized by the geometry of its unit cell, which is a section of the tiling (a parallelogram or parallelepiped) that generates the whole tiling using only translations.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] There are two special cases of the unit cell: the **primitive cell** and the **conventional cell**.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The primitive cell is a unit cell corresponding to a single lattice point, it is the smallest possible unit cell.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] In some cases, the full symmetry of a crystal structure is not obvious from the primitive cell, in which cases a conventional cell may be used.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] A conventional cell (which may or may not be primitive) is a unit cell with the full symmetry of the lattice and may include more than one lattice point.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The conventional unit cells are parallelotopes in *n* dimensions.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] A primitive cell is a unit cell that contains exactly one lattice point.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] An alternative conceptualization is to consistently pick only one of the n lattice points to belong to the given unit cell (so the other n-1 lattice points belong to adjacent unit cells).
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] where *u*1, *u*2, *u*3 are integers, translation by which leaves the lattice invariant.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] That is, for a point in the lattice **r**, the arrangement of points appears the same from **r′** = **r** + *T*→ as from **r**.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Usually, primitive cells in two and three dimensions are chosen to take the shape parallelograms and parallelepipeds, with an atom at each corner of the cell.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] This choice of primitive cell is not unique, but volume of primitive cells will always be given by the expression above.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] In addition to the parallelepiped primitive cells, for every Bravais lattice there is another kind of primitive cell called the Wigner–Seitz cell.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] In the Wigner–Seitz cell, the lattice point is at the center of the cell, and for most Bravais lattices, the shape is not a parallelogram or parallelepiped.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The Wigner–Seitz cell of the reciprocal lattice in momentum space is called the Brillouin zone.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] For each particular lattice, a conventional cell has been chosen on a case-by-case basis by crystallographers based on convenience of calculation.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] These conventional cells may have additional lattice points located in the middle of the faces or body of the unit cell.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The number of lattice points, as well as the volume of the conventional cell is an integer multiple (1, 2, 3, or 4) of that of the primitive cell.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] For any 2-dimensional lattice, the unit cells are parallelograms, which in special cases may have orthogonal angles, equal lengths, or both.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Four of the five two-dimensional Bravais lattices are represented using conventional primitive cells, as shown below.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The centered rectangular lattice also has a primitive cell in the shape of a rhombus, but in order to allow easy discrimination on the basis of symmetry, it is represented by a conventional cell which contains two lattice points.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] For any 3-dimensional lattice, the conventional unit cells are parallelepipeds, which in special cases may have orthogonal angles, or equal lengths, or both.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] Seven of the fourteen three-dimensional Bravais lattices are represented using conventional primitive cells, as shown below.
[src:crystallography/unit-cell] The other seven Bravais lattices (known as the centered lattices) also have primitive cells in the shape of a parallelepiped, but in order to allow easy discrimination on the basis of symmetry, they are represented by conventional cells which contain more than one lattice point.
